    </div>

    <div class="callout-col">
      <div class="callout">
        <div class="callout-num">1</div>
        <div>
          <p class="callout-label">Stop &amp; Jot is its own tab, not embedded in Amplify</p>
          <p class="callout-text">Amplify modifies the text. Stop &amp; Jot needs the original. Bundling them into one tab lets students amplify and jot at the same time, which is over-scaffolding. A dedicated tab makes them two separate modes the student chooses between. That's by design.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="callout">
        <div class="callout-num g">2</div>
        <div>
          <p class="callout-label">Student has to click in, nothing auto-launches</p>
          <p class="callout-text">The extension doesn't open Stop &amp; Jot when a student navigates to an article. They activate it. <em>Agency starts before the first prompt.</em> Medley's whole design philosophy is that scaffolds are tools you reach for, not things that happen to you.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="callout">
        <div class="callout-num a">3</div>
        <div>
          <p class="callout-label">Extension goes quiet once reading starts</p>
          <p class="callout-text">No banner, no countdown, no visual noise. The card is the only signal the student gets. The goal is to keep cognitive load on the reading itself and only interrupt at the breakpoint.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
