          <p class="callout-text">The card surfaces at <em>exactly the location in the text</em> where the breakpoint falls. A modal removes the student from context. A separate page breaks reading flow. Inline lets Marisol scroll back and re-read while she's responding. That's the point of a metacognitive pause.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="callout">
        <div class="callout-num g">2</div>
        <div>
          <p class="callout-label">First question is always literal recall</p>
          <p class="callout-text">Opening with inference is a barrier for a student with SLD and emerging English. <em>Literal recall is the entry ramp.</em> Questions build from there within the same reading: prediction, connection, synthesis. The progression is constrained in the LLM prompt, not left to chance.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="callout">
        <div class="callout-num a">3</div>
        <div>
          <p class="callout-label">Default response mode is driven by the student profile</p>
          <p class="callout-text">Marisol's Lexile and WIDA profile set the default tab automatically. <em>No teacher configures this.</em> A student with stronger written expression opens to the Type tab instead. The card adapts to the student, not the other way around.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="callout">
        <div class="callout-num r">4</div>
        <div>
          <p class="callout-label">All three modes and Skip are visible, nothing is buried</p>
          <p class="callout-text">Type, Voice, Sentence starter, and Skip are all present. <em>Skip is a first-class option</em>, not an escape hatch. Forcing a response before the student can continue creates punitive friction, especially for students with IEPs around task initiation. A student who skips is still reading.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="callout">
        <div class="callout-num p">5</div>
        <div>
          <p class="callout-label">Continuation text dims, reads as preview not wall</p>
          <p class="callout-text">The text below the card is lighter but still scrollable. It signals "the article continues" without removing context. <em>No animation, no overlay.</em> The card is a static embed inline in the text. Animation adds cognitive load and for SpEd students, static is the right default.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

