        <div>
          <p class="callout-label">Same student, different choices per jot</p>
          <p class="callout-text">Jot 1: Spanish, sentence frame. Jot 2: English, voice. The tags show this at a glance. <em>The student was never locked into a single mode.</em> The architecture supports mixing within one session, which is exactly what a SpEd student whose needs shift day to day actually needs.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="callout">
        <div class="callout-num r">4</div>
        <div>
          <p class="callout-label">Question progression is visible in the trail, literal to synthesis</p>
          <p class="callout-text">Jot 1 was literal recall. Jot 2 required synthesis. The trail shows Marisol how her thinking developed across the reading. <em>That's what makes this a study tool</em>, not a compliance log. The progression isn't random. The LLM is constrained to a defined question type sequence.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

